> [{quoted}](name=Destructor242,realm=NA,application-id=6kFXY1kR,discussion-id=41EO3E2i,comment-id=00010000,timestamp=2018-01-09T18:50:31.484+0000)
>
> Hey Ed, 
> I have a quick question for you. I am an arranger and composer, still in high school, but it&#x27;s my dream to be a composer for a video game company so I can combine the things I love. Do you have any tips or ideas on how this is possible or what I should do?

Hey there!

I do have a few random tips, not in any particular order:

- if you are going to be writing music for games, make sure you're a gamer (duh!). Gamers can sniff out non gamers very easily. Because music is such a time-intensive endeavor, don't spend ALL of your time playing games, but know what you have to know;
- mingle with game developers;
- embrace the idea that writing music for video games is, in fact, being a game developer who specializes in music;
- learn how to write and produce interactive music;
- be flexible with your career options. I am (and have always been) medium agnostic. I used to do a lot of TV and now I work on League. I love writing music for film as well. You don't know where your musical journey will take you, be open-minded and learn to recognize, pursue and seize opportunities!

I hope this helps! Good luck in your endeavors!

Ed the Conqueror
